The Telegraph - Calcutta : International

 Monday, November 28, 2005 

 Bhutto case

 Bhutto: Court glare

 Islamabad, Nov. 27 (PTI): A Swiss court has filed a criminal case against former Pakistan Prime Minister Benazir Bhutto on charges of slandering the deputy chairman of the National Accountability Bureau during the proceedings of a case. 

 bhutto, who lives in self-imposed exile in london and dubai, was summoned by judge fournier in geneva in connection with criminal proceedings pending against her. She was required to answer charges of aggravated money laundering on november 24 and 25, 2005, a media report here said in a report from geneva. at the start of the two-day hearing, bhutto levelled allegations against hassan wasim afzal, deputy chairman nab, saying that he had committed acts of torture against some witnesses appearing in court proceedings in pakistan, in cases against her, it said. afzal took strong exception to these remarks, the spokesman said, adding he addressed the court and lodged protest against bhutto stating that these remarks were frivolous and unfounded and were aimed at tarnishing his fair image and reputation, the news daily reported. consequently, the court registered a criminal case against bhutto on charges of slander. The case has been forwarded to the attorney-general for switzerland for proceedings against her under law.

